 from the international community with its increasing compliance since it entered the United Nations in 1971 with the rules of leading international institutions, Kent explains China's changing attitude toward international institutions in terms of the most appropriate theories of state compliance. At the same time, she argues that compliance theories on their own are not sufficient to explain the complex interaction between states and the international system and develops a broader theory to encompass China's behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Arms Control.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362636240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626362423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626362/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles